L – Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
Definition

Derived classes should be substitutable for their base classes without affecting correctness.

A child class should behave like its parent.

Bad Example
class Bird {
    void fly() {
        System.out.println("Flying");
    }
}

class Penguin extends Bird {

    void fly() {
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException();
    }
}

Problem:

Penguins cannot fly.

Thus Penguin cannot properly substitute Bird.

Violation of LSP.

Good Design
class Bird {
}

class FlyingBird extends Bird {

    void fly() {
        System.out.println("Flying");
    }
}

class Sparrow extends FlyingBird {
}

class Penguin extends Bird {
}

Now everything works correctly.

Real-Life Example

Vehicle → Car

Car can substitute Vehicle.

Vehicle → Bicycle

If Vehicle expects engine(), Bicycle cannot satisfy it.

Benefits

✔ Proper inheritance

✔ Avoids unexpected behavior

✔ Better maintainability